SIMPLE: peacock
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peacock
<hw>Pea"cock`</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧"k⟦ocr⟧k`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>pecok</ets>. <ets>Pea-</ets> in this word is from AS.
<ets>pe⟦aacute⟧</ets>, <ets>p⟦amac⟧wa</ets>, peacock, fr. L.
<ets>pavo</ets>, prob. of Oriental origin; cf. Gr. <grk>taw`s</grk>,
<grk>taw^s</grk>, Per. <ets>t⟦amac⟧us</ets>, <ets>t⟦amac⟧wus</ets>, Ar.
<ets>t⟦amac⟧w⟦umac⟧s</ets>. See <er>Cock</er> the bird.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The male of any <isa>pheasant</isa>
of the genus <gen>Pavo</gen>, of which at least two species are known,
native of Southern Asia and the East Indies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The upper tail coverts, which are long and capable of
erection, are each marked with a black spot bordered by concentric bands
of brilliant blue, green, and golden colors. The common domesticated
species is <spn>Pavo cristatus</spn>. The Javan peacock (<spn>Pavo
muticus</spn>) is more brilliantly colored than the common
species.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In common usage, the species in general or
collectively; a peafowl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Peacock butterfly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
handsome European butterfly (<spn>Hamadryas Io</spn>) having ocelli like
those of peacock.</cd> -- <col><b>Peacock fish</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European blue-striped wrasse (<spn>Labrus
variegatus</spn>); -- so called on account of its brilliant colors.
Called also <altname>cook wrasse</altname> and
<altname>cook</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Peacock pheasant</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of several species of handsome Asiatic
pheasants of the genus <gen>Polyplectron</gen>. They resemble the
peacock in color.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>peacock-blue</ent>⟦br⟧
